ations of the many passages in foreign languages, a new foreword in which Berlin biographer Michael Ignatieff explains the enduring appeal of Berlin's essay, and a new appendix that provides rich context, including excerpts from reviews and Berlin's letters, as well as a startling new interpretation of Archilochus's epigram.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aBerlin, Isaiah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardy, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIgnatieff, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIgnatieff, Michael.1 aMatthews, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVogüé, E. M. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400846634zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400846634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400846634/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles